---
import Feature from '../../layouts/Feature.astro';
import { keys } from '../../lib/keybindings';
---

<Feature
  title="CONFIGURATION"
  subtitle="TOML config with hot-reload, sensible defaults, per-platform paths."
>
  <h2>Config Format</h2>
  <p>ori-term uses a single TOML configuration file. Every setting has a sensible default -- you can run ori-term with no config file at all. When you do create one, only the settings you want to change need to be specified.</p>

  <h2>Config Location</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Windows</strong> -- <code>%APPDATA%\ori-term\config.toml</code></li>
    <li><strong>Linux</strong> -- <code>~/.config/ori-term/config.toml</code></li>
    <li><strong>macOS</strong> -- <code>~/Library/Application Support/ori-term/config.toml</code></li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Hot Reload</h2>
  <p>A file watcher monitors your config. Save the file and changes apply immediately -- no restart needed. You can also trigger a reload manually with <kbd>{keys.reloadConfig}</kbd>.</p>

  <h2>What You Can Configure</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Font</strong> -- Family, size, OpenType feature tags, <code>[[font.fallback]]</code> chain with per-fallback features and cap-height offset</li>
    <li><strong>Colors</strong> -- Built-in scheme name, light/dark auto-switch via <code>theme = "auto"</code>, individual color overrides, indexed ANSI overrides</li>
    <li><strong>Keybindings</strong> -- Override or add any key-to-action binding</li>
    <li><strong>Window</strong> -- Initial <code>columns</code>/<code>rows</code>, opacity, blur, decorations, tab bar position and density, grid padding, resize increments</li>
    <li><strong>Terminal</strong> -- Cursor shape and blink, scrollback budget, image protocol toggle and memory limits</li>
    <li><strong>Bell</strong> -- Visual (tab pulse) or audio</li>
    <li><strong>Shell</strong> -- Override default shell</li>
    <li><strong>Process model</strong> -- <code>"daemon"</code> (default, mux daemon) or <code>"embedded"</code> (single process)</li>
  </ul>
  <p>User-defined <code>[[url_patterns]]</code> with regex matchers and actions are on the roadmap; built-in URL detection ships today and covers <code>http://</code>, <code>https://</code>, <code>ftp://</code>, <code>file://</code>.</p>
</Feature>
